\title{Collectively induced many-vortices topology \\ via rotatory Dicke quantum phase transition}

\author{Priyam Das}

   \affiliation{Institute of Nuclear Science, Hacettepe University, Ankara - 06800, Turkey}

\author{Mehmet Emre Tasgin}
   \affiliation{Institute of Nuclear Science, Hacettepe University, Ankara - 06800, Turkey}
   \affiliation{to whom corresponding shall be addressed: metasgin@hacettepe.edu.tr}

\author{\"{O}zg\"{u}r E. M\"{u}stecapl\i{o}\u{g}lu}
   \affiliation{Department  of  Physics, Ko\c{c} University,  Sariyer, Istanbul, 34450, Turkey}




\begin{abstract}
We examine the superradiance of a Bose-Einstein condensate pumped with a Laguerre-Gaussian laser of high winding number, e.g., $\ell = 7$.  The laser beam transfers its orbital angular momentum to the condensate at once due to the collectivity of the superradiance. We let the spatial profile of superradiant scattering to evolve self-consistently within the equations of motion. An $\ell$-fold rotational symmetric structure emerges with the take place of rotatory superradiance. Even though the pump and the condensate profiles initially have cylindrical symmetry, we observe that it is broken to $\ell$-fold rotational symmetry after the superradiance. Self-organization of the condensate is the rotational analog of the ordering in the experiment by Esslinger and colleagues [Nature, {\bf 264}, 1301 (2010)]. We show that the critical point for the onset of the self-organization follows the form of the Dicke quantum phase transition.
\end{abstract}

\pacs{42.50.Ct 42.50.Nn 05.30.Rt}






\maketitle








Superradiance (SR) is the collective emission of an ensemble of atoms into an initially unoccupied mode \cite{dicke1954,skribanowitz1973observation}. Atoms interact with the common electromagnetic field within the extent of the pump's coherence length, and are excited to many-body states. Vacuum fluctuations in an empty photon mode stimulate the decay (radiate) of atoms to this mode \cite{andreev1993cooperative}. Hence, SR is often called as the spontaneous collective emission of an ensemble. This makes SR strongly directional\cite{Moore1999}. Probability of the ensemble to spontaneously decay to an empty mode is proportional to the exponential of the ensemble length along this direction \cite{Moore1999}. 


SR is a quantum phase transition \cite{emary2003,nagy2010,esslinger2010,hepp1973}, which can be treated with the Dicke model \cite{dicke1954}. Above a critical pump (or effective atom-photon coupling) strength, phase transition results in the macroscopic occupation of the excited states. The collectivity, which  SR induces, leads to bipartite entanglement of particles \cite{brandes2004}, photon-atom entanglement \cite{brandes2004}, single-mode nonclassicality \cite{tasgin2015single} but more importantly, to $N$-particle (collective) entanglement \cite{yukalov2004} of particles via spin-squeezing \cite{sorensen2001}. Spin-squeezing is the collective entanglement of all ($N$) of the ensemble atoms, where the measurement of a single atoms influences all the remaining ones instantaneously. In a Bose-Einstein condensate (BEC), such a collective entanglement is shown to be induced purely by the atom-atom collisions \cite{sorensen2001}. For the superradiant scattering from a BEC, this preexisting collectivity enables a smaller critical pump strength for the phase transition since BEC is already in the symmetric superradiant Dicke states \cite{dickePR1954}.

When a BEC is stirred, it does not rotate until a total of $N\hbar$ orbital angular momentum (OAM) is transferred to it \cite{pethick2002}. Experiments on the transfer of OAM to BECs via optical pumping \cite{tabosa1999,anderson2006,wright2008,moretti2009}  make us understand that there exist a critical threshold for breaking the collectivity of $N$-particle entanglement of a BEC \cite{tasgin2011}. A BEC can be made partially rotate, if the recoil energy  ($\hbar \omega_{R}$), a single atom gains, exceeds the mean atom-atom interaction energy ($U_{int}/N$) which is the situation for the optical frequencies. Therefore, regular optical pumping cannot transfer BEC to a rotatory state collectively. 


We use the collectivity \cite{yukalov2004} of rotatory SR \cite{tasgin2011} to optically induce many vortices in a BEC, at a single time. We pump the BEC with a Lauguerre-Gaussian (LG) beam of higher modes (upto $\ell = 7$), see Fig.~\ref{fig1}. We observe that the $\ell$-fold rotational symmetric density structures emerge, Fig.~\ref{fig4}, even though the pump and BEC initially have cylindrical symmetric intensities.  Interestingly, single-charged vortices emerge at the ends of the $\ell$-fold symmetric structures, see Fig.~\ref{fig4}. We determine the spatial form of the superradiant scattered pulse, $F(x,y)$, self-consistently from the equations of motion. Form of the scattered SR field is free of constraints, e.g., no mode expansion is used.

\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=7.5cm]{fig1}  
\caption{A pancake shaped BEC is illuminated with a strong LG laser of winding number $\ell$. Profile of the laser, Eq.~(\ref{PhiL}) carries $\ell\hbar$ amount of OAM per photon. Above a critical pump strength $\eta>\eta_c$ BEC superradiates the directional end-fire modes in the x-y plane due to the confinement in the z-axis. Collective transfer of OAM to the BEC can be achieved after the critical strength $\eta_c$, see Fig.~\ref{fig5}.}
\label{fig1}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

The phenomenon we observe here is the rotational analog of the self-organization of atoms, explored by Esslinger and colleagues \cite{esslinger2010}. In Ref.s~\cite{esslinger2010,nagy2008self,nagy2010}, the sudden appearance of spatial ordering arises due to the collective transfer of linear momentum via normal SR. Here, $\ell$-fold rotational ordering takes place due to the excess OAM transfer to the BEC via rotatory SR. Quantized rotations (single-charge vortices) emerge in an $\l$-fold rotational ordered form. We observe that rotatory SR emerges without a preceding normal SR, unlike Ref.~\cite{tasgin2011}, when the damping is small.

Onset (dynamics) of a superradiant spontaneous decay can be demonstrated only within the second-quantized scheme \citep{Moore1999,mustecapliouglu2000superradiant}. SR is a phase transition (PT) in the quantum ground state \cite{emary2003,nagy2010}. Nevertheless PT also shows up in semiclassical treatments as instabilities \cite{nagy2008self} on which experimental results \cite{esslinger2010} can be mapped consistently. 

Similar to Ref.~\cite{nagy2010}, we show that Hamiltonian can be transformed into the Dicke form, see Eq.~(\ref{Hdicke}). In the $\ell$-fold rotatory case, evaluation of the mode overlap integrals are not straightforward. Unlike normal SR, exact form of the recoiled (excited) wave-function and rotatory SR pulse necessitates extra care. Because, the spatial forms of the SR field and recoiled BEC evolves in time and changes the overlap integrals. We show that (i) angular momentum transferred to the BEC, $\langle\hat{L}_z\rangle$, becomes nonzero only after a critical pump strength $\eta>\eta_c$, see Fig.~\ref{fig5}. (ii) For $\eta<\eta_c$ scattered field intensity is linear with the number of BEC atoms $\sim N$, while it behaves as $\sim N^2$ above the transition $\eta>\eta_c$, see Fig.~\ref{fig6}. (iii) It is in the Dicke form such that critical pump strength ($\eta_c$) depends on the frequency of the end-fire mode ($\Delta$) and diagonal atom-field coupling ($U_0$) in the form suggested by Nagy {\it et al}. \cite{nagy2008self,esslinger2010}, see Fig.~\ref{fig7}. In this Letter, we do not trap the SR scattered pulse in a cavity in the x-y directions. However, if such a cavity would be present linear ordering \cite{esslinger2010} and rotatory ordering would be expected to emerge together.









{\it Hamiltonian}. We examine the dynamics of a pancake BEC, see Fig.~\ref{fig1}, which is illuminated with a strong LG laser of optical frequency $\omega_L$ along the symmetry axis $z$. LG pump has a spatial profile
\begin{eqnarray}
\Phi_{L}(\mathbf{r}) = E_L \:  \left(r/w_L\right)^\ell e^{-r^2/2w_L^2}e^{i \ell \phi}\cos(ik_L z)
\label{PhiL}
\end{eqnarray}
and carries an $\ell\hbar$ amount of OAM per photon. It is far-detuned to the atomic transition ($\delta_{af}\sim$GHz) which enables the adiabatic elimination of the excited internal state \cite{meystrePRA1999,tasginthesis}. $w_L$ determines the extent of the pump in the x-y plane and a $\cos(k_Lz)$ term is present due to the reflection of the pulse from the mirror \cite{esslinger2010}. Electric field amplitude of the laser is $E_L=\alpha_L\varepsilon_L$ where $|\alpha_L|^2$  is the number of pump photons and $\varepsilon_L=(\hbar\omega_L/\epsilon_0 V)^{1/2}$ with $V$ the volume of the laser cavity.

Since the BEC extends in the x-y plane and tightly confined in the z axis, directional superradiant end-fire modes emerge through the edges of the pancake along the ${\bf s}=x\hat{x}+y\hat{y}$ directions, similar to Ref.~[]. When the x-y profile of the scattered radiation has a smaller winding number, OAM is transferred to the BEC. If the scattering is collective, that is superradiant, OAM is transferred to the BEC collectively at a single time, i.e. via $e^{-Nt/\tau}$ behavior \cite{Moore1999}.

The effective Hamiltonian of the system can be written as the sum

text:
\begin{equation}
\hat{{\mathcal{H}}}_{\rm col}=\frac{g_{s}}{2} \int d^{3}{\bf r} \hat{\Psi}^{\dagger}({\bf r}) \hat{\Psi}^{\dagger}({\bf r}) \hat{\Psi}({\bf r}) \hat{\Psi}({\bf r}) \: , 
\label{Hcol}
\end{equation}

nexttext:
and the off-diagonal and diagonal atom-field interaction terms
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{{\mathcal{H}}}_{af} &=& \hbar g_{a} \int d^{3}{\bf r} \hat{\Psi}^{\dagger}({\bf r}) \hat{\Phi}^{\dagger}(r)  \Phi_{L}({\bf r}) \hat{\Psi}({\bf r}) + H.c. 
\label{Haf}
\\
\hat{{\mathcal{H}}}^{(2)}_{af} &=& 2 \hbar g_{a} \int d^{3}{\bf r} \hat{\Psi}^{\dagger}(r) \hat{\Phi}^{\dagger}(r) \hat{\Phi}({\bf r}) \hat{\Psi}({\bf r}). 
\label{Haf2}
\end{eqnarray}
Since the excited state is eliminated adiabatically \cite{meystrePRA1999,tasgin2011,tasginthesis}, $\hat{\Psi}(r)$ represents the BEC wave operator for the ground state. $\hat{H}=-\hbar^2\nabla^2/2m+V(r)$ is the first-quantized Hamiltonian for the BEC with $V(r)$ is the trap potential. $\hat{a}_L$ is the annihilation operator for the LG mode laser pump which carries $\ell\hbar$ OAM per photon. $\hat{\Phi}(\bf r)$ is the field operator for the superradiantly scattered pulse, whose spatial behavior is determined by the equations of motion. $\omega_L$ and $\omega_e$ are the frequencies for the laser and the SR end-fire mode fields. $g_a=g^2/\delta_{af}$ is the effective strength for the atom-field interaction after the adiabatic elimination, where $g$ is single atom-photon coupling strength \cite{meystrePRA1999}. 

In order to deal with the computational memory/time restrictions we perform separation of variables in the BEC and the field operators, $\hat{\Psi(r)}=\hat{f}(x,y)\hat{Z}(z)$ and $\hat{\Phi}(r)=\hat{F}(x,y)Z_f(z)$. We obtain the equation of motion (EOM) for each operator using the Heisenberg EOM, e.g., $i\hbar\dot{\hat{F}}(x,y)=[\hat{F},{\mathcal{H}}]$. (see the Supplementary \cite{Supplementary}) Since we are not dealing with correlations/entanglement, but only interested in the field amplitudes, we replace all of the operators by c-numbers, e.g. $\hat{f}(x,y)\to f(x,y)$ and $\hat{a}_L \to \alpha_L$. 

We scale the lengths by $b_r=\sqrt{\hbar \omega_r/m}$, the radial extent of the BEC. We scale the BEC wave-function $\Psi({\bf r})$ and the scattered field $\Phi({\bf r})$ with $\sqrt{N}$. Parameters $\eta=g_a\sqrt{N}|\alpha_L|$ and $U_0=g_a N$ control the strength of the off-diagonal ($\hat{{\mathcal{H}}}_{af}$) and diagonal ($\hat{{\mathcal{H}}}_{af}^{(2)}$) atom-field couplings, respectively. Off-diagonal coupling favors the macroscopic occupation the scattered field \cite{emary2003} while energy of the diagonal coupling minimizes with a microscopic scattered field. Hence, the two works against each other. If $g_s$ is negative (positive), collision term supports (works against) the SR transition \cite{nagy2008self,nagy2010}. We also introduce damping $\kappa$ to the scattered field $\Phi(\bf r)$.






{\it Vortices with $\ell$-fold symmetry}. We time evolve $\Phi({\bf r})=F(x,y)Z_f(z)$ and $\Psi({\bf r})=f(x,y)Z(z)$ self-consistently through the EOMs. In Fig.~\ref{fig2}, macroscopic OAM transfer to the BEC follows the emission peak (at $t\simeq 1.45/\omega_R$). We show that it displays collective (in-phase) behavior in Fig.~\ref{fig6}.





\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=8.5cm]{fig2}
\caption{(a) OAM transfer to the BEC follows the (b) peak in the intensity of the scattered field at $t\simeq 1.45/\omega_R$. $\eta$=50, $\Delta$=1, $U_0$=10, $\kappa$=0.4, $g_s$=0.}
\label{fig2}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

In Fig.~\ref{fig3}, we depict the time evolution of the spatial profile for both the BEC and the scattered field. During the time evolution 3-fold rotational symmetric profile, Fig.~\ref{fig3}(b), appears even though both BEC and LG pump intensity have cylindrical symmetry initially. The winding number of the laser is transformed to the 3-fold rotation symmetry. After the $\sim N^2$ scattering emerges, at $t\simeq 1.5$ in Fig.~\ref{fig3}(c), three single-charge vortices emerge at the ends of the 3-fold rotational symmetric intensity profile. By enclosing a small spatial region around the three positions, we calculate $m=\langle \Psi({\bf r})|\hat{L}_z |\Psi({\bf r}) \rangle$ and find that they carry a single charge. The presence of vortices can also be ensured by closing the pump the laser field, which traps the vortices, after $t>1.5$. In Fig.~\ref{fig2}(d) we observe the expansion of vortices when the laser field is lifted off. Remaining OAM $(m-\ell)\hbar$ is distributed to the body of the BEC.






\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=	8.0cm]{fig3}  
\caption{Time evolution of the profiles of the BEC density $|\psi(x,y)|$ and the scattered field intensity $|F(x,y)|$ for pumping with an $\ell=3$ mode LG laser above the critical pump strength $\eta<\eta_c$. 3-fold rotational symmetric structures appear (b) both in the BEC and scattered field, even though both have cylindrical symmetry initially. (c) Single-charge vortices appear at the ends of the structure such that (d) expansion of the vortices can be observed when the trapping laser field is turned off.}
\label{fig3}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

Emergence of $\ell$-fold rotational symmetric structures is common for pumping with LG lasers having the $\ell$ winding number, see Fig.~\ref{fig4}. Single-charge vortices emerge at the ends of $\ell$-fold rotational symmetric structures. When the OAM transferred to BEC is smaller than the $\ell$-fold symmetry, $m<\ell$, $\ell$-fold symmetric structures emerge again. However, in this case single-charge vortices do not emerge at the edges. OAM is distributed to the body of the BEC.



\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=	8.0cm]{fig4} 
\caption{$\ell$-fold rotational symmetric structures emerge for pumping with LG laser, profile (\ref{PhiL}), of winding number $\ell$. Appearance of single-charge vortices at the ends of $\ell$-fold structures is a common phenomenon.}
\label{fig4}
\end{center}
\end{figure}





{\it Critical pump strength}. In Fig.~\ref{fig5}, we plot the amount of OAM that can be transferred from the LG laser to the BEC for three different parameter sets, $\{ \Delta,U_0,\kappa,g_s\}$. We observe that OAM transfer to the BEC can be achieved only after a critical pump strength $\eta>\eta_c$ depending on the actual values of the diagonal coupling ($U_0$), collision ($g_s$) and damping of the scattered field ($\kappa$).

In the absence of damping, $\kappa=0$, we clearly observe the plateaus at $\langle\hat{L}_z\rangle=1$ and $\langle\hat{L}_z\rangle=2$ horizontal lines. This resistance against the the OAM transfer is due to the rotationless nature ---unless multiplies of $N\hbar$ OAM is gained \cite{pethick2002}--- of the BEC. Fig.~\ref{fig5} shows that a larger pump strength is required for the rotatory SR if we increase the diagonal coupling $U_0$ and the damping $\kappa$.
\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=8.5cm]{fig5}
\caption{OAM transfer to the BEC can be achieved only after a critical pump strength $\eta>\eta_c$, which depends on the actual values of end-fire mode frequency ($\Delta$), diagonal atom-field coupling ($U_0$), damping ($\kappa$) and atom-atom collisions ($g_s$).}
\label{fig5}
\end{center}
\end{figure}





{\it In-phase scattering}. Nature of the scattered field is depicted in Fig.~\ref{fig6}. We double the number of atoms in the condensate, $N\to 2N$, and examine the intensity of the scattered field. We observe that (i) for small pump strengths $\eta$ the nature of the scattering is linear with the number of  scatterers (BEC atoms), that is $I\sim N$. (ii) For larger $\eta$ values, the nature of the scattering approaches to the behavior $I\sim N^2$, that is BEC atoms scatter in-phase.

\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=8.5cm]{fig6}
\caption{We double the condensate atoms, $N\to 2N$, and examine the intensity of the scattered field. For small pump strength, scattering behaves as $I\sim N$, emission from independent scatterers. For larger pump strengths, scattering approaches $I\sim N^2$, emission from in-phase scatterers.}
\label{fig6}
\end{center}
\end{figure}






Due to the cylindrical symmetry and confinement of the BEC in the z-axis, SR emission emerges along the radial direction in the x-y plane, see Fig.~\ref{fig1}. Similar to Ref.s~\cite{nagy2010,Moore1999} one can expand the BEC field operator as
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{\Psi}({\bf r}) = u_g({\bf r}) \hat{c}_g + u_e({\bf r}) \hat{c}_e 
\label{eg_expansion}
\end{eqnarray}
in terms of the ground state, $u_g(\bf r)$, and recoiled (excited state) mode $u_e(\bf r)$. In difference to Ref.s~\cite{nagy2010,Moore1999}, however, exact form of the excited state $u_e(\bf r)$ is not a simple function, e.g. $\cos(kx)$ in Ref.~\cite{nagy2010} and $e^{ikx}$ in Ref.~\cite{Moore1999}, due to the introduced $\ell$-fold rotational structures, see Fig.~\ref{fig4}.  Using the expansion (\ref{eg_expansion}) we transform the Hamiltonian (\ref{Htot}) into the form (see the Supplementary~\cite{Supplementary})
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{{\mathcal{H}}} = && \hbar \Delta_{\rm eff} \hat{a}^\dagger\hat{a} + \hbar\omega_R I_e\hat{S}_z + U_0\hat{a}^\dagger\hat{a}(J_1\hat{S}_z+J_2N/2) \nonumber \\
&&+\eta\left[ (I_1\hat{a}\hat{S}_+ + I_1^*\hat{a}^\dagger\hat{S}_-)  +  (I_2\hat{a}\hat{S}_- + I_2^*\hat{a}^\dagger\hat{S}_+)  \right]
\label{Hdicke}
\end{eqnarray}
where $I_{1,2}=\int d^3{\bf r} u_{g,e}^*({\bf r}) \Phi^*({\bf r})\Phi_L^*({\bf r}) u_{e,g}({\bf r})$ are the overlap integrals for the off-diagonal term. $J_{1,2}=\int d^3{\bf r} u_{g,e}^*({\bf r}) |\Phi^*({\bf r})|^2 u_{g,e}({\bf r})$ are the overlap integrals for the diagonal atom field coupling. $I_e=\int d^3{\bf r} |\Phi^*({\bf r})|^2$ and $\Delta_{\rm eff}=\Delta-2U_0$.  Here, $\hat{S}_+=\hat{c}_e^\dagger \hat{c}_g$, $\hat{S}_+=\hat{c}_g^\dagger \hat{c}_e$ and $\hat{S}_z=(\hat{c}_e^\dagger\hat{c}_e-\hat{c}_g^\dagger\hat{c}_g)$ are the collective spin operators for the BEC system \cite{emary2003}.
Hamiltonian~(\ref{Hdicke}) is in the same form with Ref.~\cite{nagy2010} where the third term on the right hand side is the diagonal atom-field coupling which operates against the onset of SR. In Ref.~\cite{nagy2010} the two overlap integrals are equal, $I_1=I_2$.

In Fig.~\ref{fig7}, we plot the dependence of the critical pump strength $\eta_c$ on $\Delta$ and on $U_0$. Dicke model suggests \cite{nagy2008self,nagy2010} the behavior $\eta_c \sim \Delta^{1/2}$ for $U_0=\kappa=g_s=0$ and the behavior $\eta_c\sim U_0^{1/2}$ for large values of $U_0$. In Fig.~\ref{fig7}(a), we find that slope is 0.509 for the $\log\Delta$ vs $\log\eta_c$ plot. In Fig.~\ref{fig7}(b), the slope of the $\log U_0$ vs $\log\eta_c$ plot comes out to be 0.489 for large $U_0$ values.

\begin{figure}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=8.5cm]{fig7}
\caption{Dependence of the crittical pump strength on the (a) end-fire mode frequency for $U_0=\kappa=g_s=0$ and (b) on the diagonal atom-field coupling for large values of $U_0$. The slopes of the log-log plots are 0.509 and 0.489, respectively, which indicates the behavior $\eta_c\sim \Delta^{1/2}$ and $\eta_c\sim U_0^{1/2}$ as predicted by the model of Nagy {et al.} \cite{nagy2008self,nagy2010}.}
\label{fig7}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

In Fig.~\ref{fig7}, small deviations from the 0.5 slope line appear. The reason is the following. For different values of the pump strength $\eta$, time evolution yields different spatial forms for the BEC, $f(x,y)$, and the SR field, $F(x,y)$, although winding of the pumps, $\ell$, are equal. This results in different $I_{1,2}$, $J_{1,2}$ overlap integrals and changes the coefficients for the transition in Eq.~(\ref{Hdicke}). This effect deviates the behavior of $\eta_c$ from the usual form.







{\it In summary}, we show that BEC displays $\ell$-fold rotational structures when it is illuminated with a strong $\ell$-mode LG laser. $m=\langle \psi| \hat{L}_z|\psi\rangle$ amount of OAM, which depends on the system parameters, is transferred to the BEC in this process. If $m\geq \ell$, $\ell$ number of single-charge vortices appear at the ends of the symmetric structure while remain OAM $(m-\ell)\hbar$ is distributed to the body of he BEC. If $m\leq\ell$ no single-charge vortices appear.

OAM transfer to the BEC starts only after a critical pump power $\eta_c$. It follows the same behavior, $\eta_c\sim U_0^{1/2}$ for large $U_0$ and $\eta_c\sim  \Delta^{1/2}$, with the Dicke model studied in Ref.s~\cite{nagy2008self,nagy2010}. For $\eta$ small, scattering intensity is proportional to $I\sim N$ where as for large $\eta$ in-phase scattering $I\sim N^2$ appears.








